text:
Keep an eye on the night sky in October—you might catch a falling star!

The Orionid meteor shower reaches its peak on the night of Oct. 21-22, with a new moon providing ideal skywatching conditions. The Draconids will also be visible earlier in the month. 

Here's what else to watch out for!

text:
Last week, we announced our new class of astronaut candidates: 10 pilots, scientists, doctors, and explorers from across the United States. 

They're starting two years of intensive training, after which they'll be eligible for missions to low Earth orbit, the Moon, and beyond. Come join the journey with us—follow our new candidates on social media: https://go.nasa.gov/4mLeL7j

sharedPost.text:
Buzz, buzz! Our Astrobee robots have been buzzing around the International Space Station for six years!

From creating 3D maps to detecting and alerting astronauts about a simulated anomaly, the free-flying robots have marked multiple first-in-space milestones.

NASA is continuing the Astrobee mission through a collaboration with Arkisys, Inc., which was awarded a reimbursable Space Act Agreement to sustain and maintain the robotic platform moving forward. As the agency returns astronauts to the Moon, robotic helpers like Astrobee could one day take over routine tasks and support future spacecraft.

Discover what’s next: https://go.nasa.gov/46DjtOw

media.ocrText: NASA astronaut Megan McArthur poses with the Astrobee robotic free-flyers in support of the Kibo Robot Programming Challenge (Robo-Pro Challenge). The Kibo-RPC, allows students to create programs to control Astrobee, a free-flying robot aboard the International Space Station (ISS).

Astronaut and Expedition 69 Flight Engineer Sultan Alneyadi observes a free-flying Astrobee robotic assistant during the testing of its operations for an upcoming student competition to control the robotic devices.

One of the International Space Station's free-flying robots, Astrobee, was pictured by NASA astronaut and Expedition 71 Flight Engineer Tracy C. Dyson during a Zero Robotics tech demonstration. Zero Robotics allows students on Earth to write software to control the robots and observe their performance inside the orbiting laboratory.

text:
Hey kid… wanna see a conjunction?
 
Before dawn on Sept. 19, you can! Nestled up to the crescent moon, you can find Venus and Regulus, one of the brightest nighttime stars. These three form a conjunction, meaning they appear near each other despite being far apart in space.

text:
Meet our new class of future astronauts!

On Monday, Sept. 22, we're introducing our 2025 class of astronaut candidates, selected from over 8,000 applications. Tune in at 12:30 p.m. EDT (1630 UTC) for the reveal: https://youtu.be/frX3-5xuGQs

Afterwards, they'll be taking your questions in a Reddit AMA ("Ask Me Anything") on the r/nasa Reddit community. Send in your questions anytime Monday afternoon, and our newly-announced explorers will be on to respond at 5:30 p.m. EDT (2130 UTC): https://www.reddit.com/r/nasa/

Our astronaut candidates will undergo two years of training before graduating as flight-eligible astronauts for missions to low Earth orbit, the Moon, and ultimately Mars. Ad astra!

text:
It's a bird! It's a plane! ...It's a super-jet! 🦸

NASA's James Webb Space Telescope captured this blowtorch of seething gases erupting from a volcanically growing monster star. Stretching across eight light-years, the length of the stellar eruption is approximately twice the distance between our Sun and our next-nearest stars in the Alpha Centauri system. The size and strength of this stellar jet are rare, according to researchers.

The jets from protostars we observe are mainly from low-mass stars, but the discovery of this particular jet offers evidence that protostellar jets must scale up with the mass of the star powering them: The more massive the stellar engine propelling the plasma, the larger the gusher's size.
 
Learn more: https://go.nasa.gov/41YvgFt

media.ocrText: Gaseous yellow-orange filaments look like a flower seen from the side and tilted slightly from upper left to lower right, slightly higher than the center of the frame. Extending from the flower to the upper left and lower right are red gas outflows that have an overall shape of tall, narrow triangles with rounded tips. Each red triangle is made up of wavy, irregular lines. Dozens of stars are scattered across the field. One particularly bright white star with eight diffraction spikes is located at the top of the yellow rose. Another bright blue star with even more prominent diffraction spikes is to its lower left. The background of space is black. Credit: NASA, ESA, CSA, STScI, Yu Cheng (NAOJ); Image Processing: Joseph DePasquale (STScI)
